WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.730
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.010 --> 00:00:07.150
- Good afternoon, everybody.

00:00:07.150 --> 00:00:08.160
I'm Jane Kamensky.

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:10.490
I'm the director of the
Schlesinger Library.

00:00:10.490 --> 00:00:13.650
I want to welcome you on behalf
of the Radcliffe Institute

00:00:13.650 --> 00:00:17.150
and Schlesinger, one
of its major programs,

00:00:17.150 --> 00:00:21.960
on this, the first big
public event of Schlesinger's

00:00:21.960 --> 00:00:23.670
75th anniversary year.

00:00:23.670 --> 00:00:26.900
So we've actually invited
you to a birthday party

00:00:26.900 --> 00:00:32.250
and there will be plenty of food
at the reception afterwards.

00:00:32.250 --> 00:00:35.010
We're taking in this
75th anniversary

00:00:35.010 --> 00:00:39.870
year a year-long look
back at our origins,

00:00:39.870 --> 00:00:46.200
at the journey we've taken since
1943, at how far we've come,

00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:49.380
and especially taking
stock and thinking

00:00:49.380 --> 00:00:53.280
about new directions in future.

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:56.820
Calling the year 2018
our 75th anniversary

00:00:56.820 --> 00:01:00.000
actually looks to
Schlesinger Library's second

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.070
of three foundings.

00:01:02.070 --> 00:01:04.690
The first was the
collection that

00:01:04.690 --> 00:01:08.550
served what was initially called
the Harvard Annex and then

00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:12.040
later Radcliffe College
in the late 19th century.

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:15.720
But the anniversary we're
celebrating this year,

00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:19.710
dating to 1943 in the middle
of the Second World War

00:01:19.710 --> 00:01:25.020
some 23 years after American
women won the right to vote,

00:01:25.020 --> 00:01:28.455
was the moment when the
Radcliffe alumna Maude Wood

00:01:28.455 --> 00:01:32.610
Park, class of '98,
donated a large collection

00:01:32.610 --> 00:01:35.520
of suffrage-related
material to create

00:01:35.520 --> 00:01:38.520
what was called the Woman's
Rights Collection at Radcliffe

00:01:38.520 --> 00:01:39.690
College.

00:01:39.690 --> 00:01:42.640
This was a big
collection for its time.

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:45.690
It included 30 cartons
of manuscripts,

00:01:45.690 --> 00:01:48.810
more than 300 books
and periodicals,

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:53.160
some assorted objects,
including possibly the suffrage

00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:56.700
wagon that our photographs
show pulling up

00:01:56.700 --> 00:02:01.380
to Longfellow Hall on Women's
Equality Day, August 26,

00:02:01.380 --> 00:02:03.960
of 1943.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:06.810
That's the anniversary of the
passage of the 19th Amendment

00:02:06.810 --> 00:02:08.580
through the final state.

00:02:08.580 --> 00:02:11.580
The Woman's Rights
Collection was that year

00:02:11.580 --> 00:02:14.620
given a proverbial
room of its own,

00:02:14.620 --> 00:02:17.940
which was a small padlocked
space in Longfellow Hall

00:02:17.940 --> 00:02:21.530
now part of Harvard's
Graduate School of Education.

00:02:21.530 --> 00:02:24.450
The first year for
which we have records

00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:27.150
of the use of the
Women's Rights Collection

00:02:27.150 --> 00:02:32.610
is 1949 and seven researchers
used it that year.

00:02:32.610 --> 00:02:35.910
So here we are, 7 and
1/2 decades later.

00:02:35.910 --> 00:02:39.660
Schlesinger houses more than
4,000 manuscript collections

00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:43.800
and 130,000 books-- a number
that grows every day--

00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:47.370
enough to fill three
capacious vaults on site

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:51.270
and much more in Harvard's
remote depository.

00:02:51.270 --> 00:02:54.540
We are a vibrant living
library, building

00:02:54.540 --> 00:02:57.360
on strengths like the
June Jordan collection

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:02.010
that came to us 15 years ago and
provides the genesis of today's

00:03:02.010 --> 00:03:04.410
event, and building
on those strengths

00:03:04.410 --> 00:03:07.650
to strike out in
complementary directions

00:03:07.650 --> 00:03:10.710
as well as to break new ground.

00:03:10.710 --> 00:03:13.830
We will break new
ground literally

00:03:13.830 --> 00:03:15.930
at the end of this
anniversary year, late

00:03:15.930 --> 00:03:19.290
next fall, when we thoroughly
renovate our main building

00:03:19.290 --> 00:03:23.250
to improve our public
learning and work spaces.

00:03:23.250 --> 00:03:25.980
And we break new
ground intellectually

00:03:25.980 --> 00:03:28.500
with acquisitions,
like one you might

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:32.055
have read about last week,
the papers of Angela Davis.

00:03:32.055 --> 00:03:33.406
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:37.310 --> 00:03:41.080
Our work in the library is
meticulous and detailed,

00:03:41.080 --> 00:03:43.580
so just to give you
a sense of scale,

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:47.200
the Angela Davis papers
are over 150 cartons--

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:50.800
nearly half the size of that
whole founding collection--

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:56.890
and it'll take nearly two
years of full-time staff work

00:03:56.890 --> 00:04:00.580
to sort, describe,
preserve, stabilize,

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:04.270
and ready Angela Davis'
papers for researchers.

00:04:04.270 --> 00:04:07.690
Our work, in other words,
is staff-intensive.

00:04:07.690 --> 00:04:10.750
The depth of training that
our curators, archivists,

00:04:10.750 --> 00:04:14.380
processors, staff leaders,
and reference librarians

00:04:14.380 --> 00:04:18.279
have is known throughout
the industry and is,

00:04:18.279 --> 00:04:19.959
among other things,
I think, one of

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:23.800
our key competitive
advantages in the world

00:04:23.800 --> 00:04:25.250
of special collections.

00:04:25.250 --> 00:04:27.250
There are a lot of
Schlesinger staff here today,

00:04:27.250 --> 00:04:29.625
and if I could ask that you
would stand up so that we can

00:04:29.625 --> 00:04:31.438
applaud what you do, please.

00:04:31.438 --> 00:04:32.905
